        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         This is all still very wild to me, and it wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be possible without all of you reading, sharing, engaging, and pushing back \xe2\x80\x93 thank you!
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         With the benefit of hindsight, it seems like each of Not Boring\xe2\x80\x99s first two years have been defined by one thing:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-top: 0;">
         <li style="margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">
           <strong>
            Year 1:
           </strong>
           <strong>
            Newsletter Growth and Survival
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">
           <strong>
            Year 2: Not Boring Capital
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The first year, I started writing the
         <strong>
          newsletter
         </strong>
         full-time while Puja was pregnant and I was unemployed and making no money, hoping that it would grow enough that it could at least pay rent. I was surprised it grew as fast as it did and that it got big enough to be a real business. I was also surprised that writing a newsletter helped me get access to invest in early-stage companies.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         So the second year, I launched
         <strong>
          Not Boring Capital
         </strong>
         to invest in startups and help tell their stories. That had an impact on the newsletter, too: I wrote more about startups and web3 in the past year because that\xe2\x80\x99s where I was spending all of my time, and less about public companies. When I decided to go for it, I didn\xe2\x80\x99t have expectations beyond, \xe2\x80\x9cThis will be easier to manage than needing to spin up a new SPV every time I want to invest.\xe2\x80\x9d Writing a newsletter and managing the fund \xe2\x80\x93 through Fund I and into Fund II, with a growing number of portfolio companies to support \xe2\x80\x93 has been a
         <strong>
          ton of work, and I\xe2\x80\x99ve loved every second of it
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I didn\xe2\x80\x99t really have a long-term plan. I was just riding the growth.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         When I started talking to LPs to raise Fund I, and even into Fund II, I\xe2\x80\x99d often get a question along the lines of:
         <strong>
          \xe2\x80\x9cWhat do you want this to become in the next 5-10 years?\xe2\x80\x9d
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Depending on when you asked me that question, I probably gave a different answer, but most often, my answer was something like, \xe2\x80\x9cNot sure! I\xe2\x80\x99m just having fun and following this wherever it takes me!\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         That was partially because I was working so much I didn\xe2\x80\x99t have time to plan ahead, partially because the curve felt so steep that any answer would get stale in a couple of months, and partially because, after a decade of working for only two companies, having all of that
         <strong>
          freedom felt really great
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Any good manager will tell you that having employees feels like a bigger responsibility, and challenge, than having a boss. When someone puts their career in your hands, the pressure is on to deliver. That felt like a lot to take on again when the solo thing was so much fun.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          Fun doesn\xe2\x80\x99t mean easy
         </strong>
         . Being solo has meant working seven days per week, every week, for two years (with a week-long break when Dev was born and a recharge over the holidays). Running the fund and newsletter has meant that my calendar is this weird Tetris of meetings whenever founders happen to be free combined with couple-hour writing blocks squeezed in where possible. I work weekends partially because it\xe2\x80\x99s the only time I can be sure there won\xe2\x80\x99t be any distractions. Puja is a hero for making it work, and I\xe2\x80\x99m grateful that we both work from home so I can still spend a ton of time with her and Dev throughout the week.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Anyway, it\xe2\x80\x99s been a lot, but it\xe2\x80\x99s been working.
         <strong>
          Hard can be comfortable when it\xe2\x80\x99s familiar
         </strong>
         . Even if hiring people would take off some of the load (post-onboarding), I thought that bringing more people in would necessarily mean a drop-off in content quality. Last June, in
         <em>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkN1qhDAQhZ_G3K3k33iRi0LZ15CJGd1QTSTGim_fdIUWJhM4w5nDfCMUnFO-7Jb2Qn7bUK4NbcRzX7AUzOTYMQ_BW6a5EUr2xFvpmVGGhH2YMuIKYbElH0i2wy1hhBJSfDso5Yq87NQ5gN47NoKUVHsx9Ya5XmqPVE3c37lw-IBxRIvfmK8UkSz2Vcq2N-Kj4c9a53m2MRWXcohzO6YqbfVV6XFrD1ihEc_q-DxJsJxyTiVjjCtJu5a3UyeNEb1m3o0KKLaSxe1iAhpJ15m3--H2AuNX3b2SbP-y6vjrBSsu70G9cqj_esRQrgEjuAX9DaDcHN9Ihhkj5srXD1AqPdlrw3RnBJP3wZWQYj3jWitSk32qrvgf-gOzwIoi" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           Not Boring AMA
          </a>
         </em>
         , I wrote probably the clearest encapsulation of my thinking in response to
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uwyAQhU8TlhYMP4YFi0pVrmFhPHFobLAAN_Lti-NFJQQPjd68mc-7inPKh91SqeS8hnpsaCO-y4K1YiZ7wTyEyTIFmkthyGTFxLTUJJThkRFXFxZb845k28cleFdDih8HpSDJ0z6c1oZqT6UGNQoAlNKPqPrRcQrUX7lunwJGjxZ_MR8pIlnss9at3PjXDe7t1Hc4J-p8Ws-fi-74aaJUV_fSBBNU91qBMYYzYL0BceP35v8GSoIFCkAFYwykoH0H3aMXWnOj2DR66Sh2gsXtYNzdBF1n6Mo-tt7-dQaSbGOqY8ohzq38eroVl0-hLT20d91jqMeA0Y0LThePemH9EBpmjJgb7mlwtcEURmmmes2ZuPZvwCQzDJSSpCVPqbnif-gfjpOLSw" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Tanay\xe2\x80\x99s question
         </a>
         , \xe2\x80\x9cHow might Not Boring \xe2\x80\x98fail\xe2\x80\x99 from here on in?\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           Second, Not Boring could fail if I try to turn this into something it\xe2\x80\x99s not. People often ask when I\xe2\x80\x99m going to hire a team, or add more writers, or even get a ghost writer to take off some of the load. The
           <strong>
            answer is probably never
           </strong>
           , unless there are incredibly compelling opportunities to do so or areas that I know you want to learn about that I just don\xe2\x80\x99t think I can analyze well and that no one else covers particularly well.
          </em>
         </p>
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           No one wants
           <strong>
            more
           </strong>
           content. They want something unique that they can\xe2\x80\x99t get anywhere else. The more I try to systematize this and bring in other people to do the creative work for me in the name of more, the faster I fail.
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Reading back on that answer, I made a couple of mistakes:
        </p>
        <ol style="margin-top: 0;">
         <li style="margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">
           I
           <strong>
            framed the team question the wrong way
           </strong>
           , viewing more people as just a way to add more content as opposed to adding their own unique twist.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">
           I thought
           <strong>
            too narrowly in terms of just the newsletter
           </strong>
           , and not the bigger thing I was starting to build across the media business and fund.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">
           I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t predict the
           <strong>
            quality of the people
           </strong>
           I would be able to hire in the future.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ol>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         If you let a therapist in my head, I\xe2\x80\x99m sure they\xe2\x80\x99d come up with more interesting explanations for why I thought there was something special and honorable about going it alone. The long and short of it, though, is that what I\xe2\x80\x99d been doing seemed to be working, and
         <strong>
          I didn\xe2\x80\x99t want to ruin the magic
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But over the past couple of months, and especially as I was writing this quarter\xe2\x80\x99s update to Not Boring Capital\xe2\x80\x99s LPs (the fund\xe2\x80\x99s investors, or Limited Partners) over the past week, I realized that there was
         <strong>
          too much cool stuff to do to
         </strong>
         <em>
          <strong>
           not
          </strong>
         </em>
         <strong>
          bring some smart people on to do it.
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         There are more ways that we can use Not Boring to put our thumbs on the scale for the founders we back than I could manage myself, even with a suite of new products that makes it easier than ever to get leverage from small teams.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         And there are more areas that fascinate me and that I\xe2\x80\x99d like to invest in than I can possibly get smart on by myself, or understand deeply enough to make early, high-conviction investments. Pretty much every day, I read about a new company or scientific advance and think, \xe2\x80\x9cDamn, I wish I had time to understand this better\xe2\x80\x9d and \xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99d love to write a Not Boring on this.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Plus, I think if this is just my ideas, it stagnates. We need some fresh spice.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         So we\xe2\x80\x99re going to grow the team, but we\xe2\x80\x99re going to do it in a Not Boring way: we\xe2\x80\x99re going to create a
         <strong>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkN-KhSAQh58m706oaccuvFhYzmuEf6aSUxo2bfT26ynYBUdhhh-f8zmDMKZ86jVtSD5Xj-cKOsKxzYAImewb5D54zVquGik64rXwTElFwtYPGWAxYdaYdyDrbufgDIYUrwSlXJJJD54qa7n0hnLmALw1nFExCNdaAOpvrtl9gOhAww_kM0Ugs54Q161qvir-Kuc4jjomtCmHONYuldZaCid4uJRWyBf5AS7FtJyPqnmV7PdBguaUcyoYY1wK-qx5PTyFUk3XMm-dNBRqweJ6ssZUgi4jr7fdbmjcu1AWkvUftYzfk1lgvgZl3768yx4Dnj1EY2fwtwq8jV5y-hHi53Pge4PFo-haxdqnapi4Vy-uJOsYb1tJCtmnkor_0F9OY46e" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           Liquid Super Team
          </a>
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
